<paragraph blockId="69.[151,1436,152,938]" pageId="69" pageNumber="70">
More than 20 nominal species have been assigned at various times to this genus worldwide (
<bibRefCitation author="Calder, D. R." box="[1273,1423,712,738]" pageId="69" pageNumber="70" pagination="1 - 107" refId="ref52713" refString="Calder, D. R. (1988) Shallow-water hydroids of Bermuda: the Athecatae. Royal Ontario Museum, Life Sciences Contributions, 148, 1 - 107." type="journal article" year="1988">Calder 1988</bibRefCitation>
). Over the past century, most authors have recognized no more than three of these as valid: 
<taxonomicName authority="porpita (Linnaeus, 1758)" authorityName="porpita (Linnaeus" authorityYear="1758" baseAuthorityName="Linnaeus" baseAuthorityYear="1758" class="Hydrozoa" family="Porpitidae" genus="Porpita" kingdom="Animalia" order="Anthoathecata" pageId="69" pageNumber="70" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="species" species="porpita">
<emphasis box="[1250,1435,752,777]" italics="true" pageId="69" pageNumber="70">Porpita porpita</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Linnaeus, C." box="[159,345,792,818]" pageId="69" pageNumber="70" refId="ref59798" refString="Linnaeus, C. (1758) Systema naturae per regna tria naturae, secundum classes, ordines, genera, species cum characteribus, differentiis, synonymis, locis. Editio decima, reformata. Laurentii Salvii, Holmiae, 823 pp." type="book" year="1758">Linnaeus, 1758</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
from the Indian Ocean, 
<taxonomicName authority="(O. F. Muller, 1776 b)" baseAuthorityName="O. F. Muller" baseAuthorityYear="1776" box="[655,1041,792,818]" class="Hydrozoa" family="Porpitidae" genus="Porpita" kingdom="Animalia" order="Anthoathecata" pageId="69" pageNumber="70" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="species" species="umbella">
<emphasis box="[655,781,792,817]" italics="true" pageId="69" pageNumber="70">P. umbella</emphasis>
(O.F. 
<bibRefCitation author="Muller, O. F." box="[862,1033,792,818]" pageId="69" pageNumber="70" pagination="290 - 297" refId="ref61657" refString="Muller, O. F. (1776 b) Beschreibung zwoer Medusen. Beschaftigungen der Berlinischen Gesellschaft Naturforschender Freunde, 2, 290 - 297." type="journal article" year="1776">Müller, 1776b</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
from the Atlantic Ocean, and 
<taxonomicName authority="Lesson, 1826" authorityName="Lesson" authorityYear="1826" class="Hydrozoa" family="Tubulariidae" genus="Tubularia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Anthoathecata" pageId="69" pageNumber="70" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="species" species="pacifica">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="69" pageNumber="70">P. pacifica</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Lesson, R. P." box="[254,412,832,858]" pageId="69" pageNumber="70" refId="ref59550" refString="Lesson, R. P. (1826) Voyage autour du monde, execute par l'ordre du Roi, sur la corvette de sa majeste, &quot; la Coquille, &quot; pendant les annees 1822, 1823, 1824 et 1825. Histoire naturelle, zoologie. Atlas. Zoophytes. A. Bertrand, Paris, 16 pl." type="journal volume" year="1826">Lesson, 1826</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
from the Pacific Ocean. 
<bibRefCitation author="Moser, F." box="[715,878,832,858]" pageId="69" pageNumber="70" pagination="1 - 541" refId="ref61523" refString="Moser, F. (1925) Die Siphonophoren der Deutschen Sudpolar - Expedition 1901 - 1903. Deutsche Sudpolar-Expedition 1901 - 1903, 17 (Zoologie 9), 1 - 541." type="journal article" year="1925">Moser (1925)</bibRefCitation>
and 
<bibRefCitation author="Totton, A. K." box="[939,1101,832,858]" pageId="69" pageNumber="70" pagination="1 - 162" refId="ref65848" refString="Totton, A. K. (1954) Siphonophora of the Indian Ocean, together with systematic and biological notes on related specimens from other oceans. Discovery Reports, 27, 1 - 162." type="journal article" year="1954">Totton (1954)</bibRefCitation>
have been followed here in regarding these three as conspecific, with the name 
<taxonomicName authorityName="porpita (Linnaeus" authorityYear="1758" box="[772,889,872,898]" class="Hydrozoa" family="Porpitidae" genus="Porpita" kingdom="Animalia" order="Anthoathecata" pageId="69" pageNumber="70" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="species" species="porpita">
<emphasis box="[772,787,872,897]" italics="true" pageId="69" pageNumber="70">P</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[803,889,872,897]" italics="true" pageId="69" pageNumber="70">porpita</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
having priority. For reviews of the taxonomy and nomenclature of this genus, see 
<bibRefCitation author="Bigelow, H. B." box="[576,760,912,938]" pageId="69" pageNumber="70" pagination="171 - 402" refId="ref50508" refString="Bigelow, H. B. (1911) Reports on the scientific results of the expedition to the eastern tropical Pacific, in charge of Alexander Agassiz, by the U. S. Fish Commission steamer &quot; Albatross &quot;, from October 1904, to March, 1905, Lieut. Commander L. M. Garrett, U. S. N., commanding. XXIII. The Siphonophorae. Memoirs of the Museum of Comparative Zoology at Harvard College, 38, 171 - 402." type="journal article" year="1911">Bigelow (1911)</bibRefCitation>
and 
<bibRefCitation author="Calder, D. R." box="[817,984,912,938]" pageId="69" pageNumber="70" pagination="1 - 107" refId="ref52713" refString="Calder, D. R. (1988) Shallow-water hydroids of Bermuda: the Athecatae. Royal Ontario Museum, Life Sciences Contributions, 148, 1 - 107." type="journal article" year="1988">Calder (1988)</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
